th century                 || [[Bruce Alexander Cook]]     || '' [[Blind Justice (novel)|Blind Justice]]'' || 1994\n|-\n|[[Lord John Grey (character)|Lord John Grey]] || England, [[Prussia]],<br>[[Scotland]] and [[Jamaica]] || 1756\u20131761 || [[Diana Gabaldon]] || ''[[Lord John and the Hellfire Club]]'' || 1998<ref name=\"LJ note\"/><ref name=\"Gabaldon Grey\"/><ref name=\"EW Devils\"/>\n|-\n|[[Samuel Johnson]]/[[James Boswell]]   || England                 || data-sort-value=\"1700\"| 18th century                 || [[Lillian de la Torre]]      || \"[[The Great Seal of England]]\"       || 1943<ref name=\"DLT obit\"/><ref name=\"DLT bio\"/>\n|-\n|[[Dick Darwent]]               || England                         || 1815                  || [[John Dickson Carr]]        || ''[[The Bride of Newgate]]''          || 1950<ref name=\"Carr\"/>\n|-\n|[[Matthew Hawkwood]]           || England                         ||data-sort-value=\"1700\"|  18th century                 || [[James McGee (author)|James McGee]]       || ''[[Trigger Men]]''     || 1985\n|-\n|[[Sergeant Cribb (character)|Sergeant Cribb]]      || England     ||data-sort-value=\"1800\"|  19th century          || [[Peter Lovesey]]            || ''[[Wobble to Death]]''               || 1970\n|-\n|[[Thomas Pitt (fictional character)|Thomas Pitt]]<ref name=\"PW Picker 2010\"/>  || England  || data-sort-value=\"1800\"|19th century  || [[Anne Perry]] || ''[[The Cater Street Hangman]]''   || 1979\n|-\n|[[William Monk]]<ref name=\"PW Picker 2010\"/> || England           || data-sort-value=\"1800\"|19th century          || [[Anne Perry]]                  || ''[[The Face of a Stranger]]''     || 1990\n|-\n|[[Mrs. Jeffries]]              || England                         ||data-sort-value=\"1800\"| 19th century          || [[Emily Brightwell]]         || ''[[The Inspector and Mrs. Jeffries]]''    || 1993\n|-\n|[[Edmund Blackstone]]          || England                         || 1820s                 || [[Richard Falkirk]]          || ''[[Blackstone (novel)|Blackstone]]'' || 1972\n|-\n|[[Benjamin January]]           || [[New Orleans]]                 || 1833                  || [[Barbara Hambly]]           || ''[[A Free Man of Color (Hambly novel)|A Free Man of Color]]'' || 1997\n|-\n|[[Yashim the Eunuch]]          || [[Ottoman Empire]]              || 1836                  || [[Jason Goodwin]]            || ''[[The Janissary Tree]]''            || 2006\n|-\n|[[Uncle Abner]]                || [[West Virginia]]               || data-sort-value=\"1850\"|Mid-19th century      || [[Melville Davisson Post]]   || \"[[The Angel of the Lord]]\"           || 1911<ref name=\"Abner\"/>\n|-\n|[[Erast Fandorin]]             || [[Russia]], [[Japan]], etc.     || 1876\u20131914             || [[Boris Akunin]]             || ''[[The Winter Queen (novel)|The Winter Queen]]''   || 1998\n|-\n|[[Ambrose Bierce (character)|Ambrose Bierce]] || [[San Francisco]] || data-sort-value=\"1860\"|Late 19th century    || [[Oakley Hall]]              || ''Ambrose Bierce and the Queen of Spades''          || 1998\n|-\n|William Murdoch                || [[Toronto]]                     || 1890s                 || [[Maureen Jennings]]         || ''[[Except the Dying (novel)|Except the Dying]]''   || 1997\n|-\n|[[Sister Pelagia]]             || [[Russia]]                      || 1890s or Early 20th century  || [[Boris Akunin]]      || ''Pelagia and the White Bulldog''     || 2000 (Russian)<br>2006 (English)\n|-\n|[[Amelia Peabody]]<ref name=\"PW Picker 2010\"/>     || [[Egypt]]   || 1884\u20131923             || [[Elizabeth Peters]]         || ''[[Crocodile on the Sandbank]]''     || 1975\n|-\n|[[Alexander von Reisden]]      || [[Boston]]                      || data-sort-value=\"1900\"|Early 20th century    || [[Sarah Smith (writer)|Sarah Smith]]    || ''[[The Vanished Child]]'' || 1992\n|-\n|[[Simon Ziele]]                || [[New York City]]               || data-sort-value=\"1900\"|Early 20th century    || [[Stefanie Pintoff]]         || ''[[In the Shadow of Gotham]]''       || 2009\n|-\n|[[Mary Russell (character)|Mary Russell]]  || Worldwide           ||data-sort-value=\"1900\"| Early 20th century    || [[Laurie R. King]]           || ''[[The Beekeeper's Apprentice]]''    || 1994\n|-\n|[[Joe Sandilands]]             || [[Colonial India]], [[Europe]]  || 1920s/1930s           || [[Barbara Cleverly]]         || ''[[The Last Kashmiri Rose]]''        || 2001\n|-\n|Bernie G\u00fcnther<ref name=\"PW Picker 2010\"/>  || [[Berlin]]         || 1934\u20131954             || [[Philip Kerr]]              || ''[[March Violets]]''                 || 1989\n|-\n|[[Laetitia Talbot]]            || [[Crete]], [[Burgundy]], [[Athens]] || 1920s             || [[Barbara Cleverly]]         || ''[[The Tomb of Zeus]]''              || 2007\n|-\n|[[Phryne Fisher]]              || [[Melbourne]]                   || 1920s                 || [[Kerry Greenwood]]          || ''[[Cocaine Blues (novel)|Cocaine Blues]]'' || 1989\n|-\n|Professor John Stableford      || [[England]]                     || 1930s                 || [[:de:Rob Reef]]             ||  ''Stableford on Golf''      || 2013\n|-\n|Lady Georgiana                 || England/Scotland                || 1930s                 || [[Rhys Bowen]]               || ''Her Royal Spyness''                 || 2007\n|-\n|Alexei Korolev                 || Moscow                          || 1936                  || William Ryan                 || ''The Holy Thief''                 || 2010\n|-\n|Kasper Meier                   || [[Berlin]]                      || 1946                  || [[Ben Fergusson]]            || ''The Spring of Kasper Meier''        || 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london24.com/entertainment/book_review_the_spring_of_kasper_meier_by_ben_fergusson_1_3689195 |title=Book review: ''The Spring of Kasper Meier'' by Ben Fergusson |first=Beth |last=Wyatt |publisher=London24.com |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=4 October 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329164751/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2h5pyDsVSQVQ5rfSbHwqgN3/the-spring-of-kasper-meier-by-ben-fergusson |archivedate=March 29, 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2h5pyDsVSQVQ5rfSbHwqgN3/the-spring-of-kasper-meier-by-ben-fergusson |title=''The Spring Of Kasper Meier'' by Ben Fergusson |publisher=[[BBC Radio 2]] |date=2014 |accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://histmyst.org/ The Detective and the Toga], a listing/guide for Ancient Roman mysteries\n* [http://www.historicalnovelsociety.org The Historical Novel Society], an international organization for historical fiction writers and readers\n\n{{Crime fiction}}\n{{Fictional espionage navbox}}\n{{Historical fiction}}\n\n[[Category:Historical novels subgenres]]\n[[Category:Literary genres]]\n[[Category:Mystery fiction]]\n[[Category:Historical mystery| ]]\n\n[[zh:\u63a8\u7406\u5c0f\u8aaa#\u6b77\u53f2\u63a8\u7406]]<!-- points to section within Mystery article on zh: -->\n", "name_user": "Juanmakabulos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historical_mystery"}
{"title_page": "Forager (video game)", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Forager\n| image = \n| developer = [[HopFrog]]\n| publisher = [[Humble Bundle]]\n| engine = [[GameMaker Studio]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = {{Collapsible list|title=April 18, 2019|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left;\n| '''Microsoft Windows'''|April 18, 2019\n| '''PlayStation 4'''|July 30, 2019\n| '''Nintendo Switch'''|July 30, 2019\n}}\n| genre = [[Open-world]], [[Adventure Game]], [[Survival game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n| director =\n| producer = \n| designer = Mariano Cavallero \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| composer = \n}}\n'''''Forager''''' is an [[open-world]] [[Adventure Game|adventure]] game developed by American studio [[HopFrog]]<ref>https://twitter.com/_hopfrog</ref> and published by [[Humble Bundle]]. The game was officially released for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[Linux]] in April 2019, later becoming available for [[PlayStation 4]],[[Nintendo Switch]], [[Xbox One]], and Mobile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobilemodegaming.com/2020/04/20/hopfrogs-forager-announced-for-mobile-on-its-1st-anniversary/|title=HopFrog's \u2018Forager\u2019 Announced For Mobile on Its 1st Anniversary|date=2020-04-20|website=Mobile Mode Gaming|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> \n\nIn ''Forager'', the player progresses by obtaining resources that spawn throughout the world, crafting new buildings, objects, and tools, solving [[Puzzle video game|puzzles]], and collecting money to buy new lands to explore and utilize.\n\n==Gameplay==\nForager combines mechanics commonly seen in [[Incremental_game|idle games]] with those of an adventure or exploration game. <ref name=\"RPS-Forager\">{{cite web |last1=Peel |first1=Jeremy |title=Wot I Think: Forager |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/04/26/forager-review/ |website=Rock Paper Shotgun |publisher=Rock Paper Shotgun |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref> With resources that respawn at a very high rate, the player will find themselves able to harvest massive amounts for crafting and leveling, eventually leading to [[Automation|automated]] systems to collect resources and produce other products and goods.\n\nThe leveling system in the game consists of a large grid of unlockable perks, which also may unlock new tools or craftable objects. Everything the player does from harvesting resources, to crafting objects, to killing enemies, has a positive impact on their [[Experience_point|XP]] used to advance levels.\n\nThe player is able to [[Simulation|simulate]] a variety of tasks related to [[cooking]], [[economics]], [[engineering]], [[farming]], [[fishing]], [[hunting]], [[Magic_system|magic]], [[manufacturing]], [[mining]], and more.\n\nBy obtaining money through crafting, skills, looting, and economic tasks, the player is able to purchase more lands to expand their base, explore new areas, and obtain new classes of resources or encounter new enemies and other [[Non-player_character|NPC]].\n\n<br />\n<br />\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = \n| state = plain\n| align = right\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = PC:&nbsp;78/100 <ref name=\"Matacritic-Forager\">{{cite web |title=Forager for PC Reviews - Metacritic |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/forager |website=Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref><br />\nNS:&nbsp;75/100<ref name=\"Metacritic-switch\">{{cite web |title=Forager for Switch Reviews - Metacritic |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/forager |website=Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 = [[PCWorld]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"PCWorld-forager\">{{cite web |last1=Dingman |first1=Hayden |title=Forager review: Mindlessly mining the minutes away |url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/3394862/forager-review.html |website=PCWorld |publisher=PCWorld}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Forager'' received \"generally favorable\" reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"Matacritic-Forager\"/> \n\nNathan Grayson wrote a review on [[Kotaku]] calling ''Forager'' an \"extremely well-made\" game and called it \"obviously a labor of love\" while also noting that the game was \"a crafting game stripped down to its very bones\" and stating that players may prefer a game with \"more than pure progression\". <ref name=\"Kotaku-forager-review\">{{cite web |last1=Grayson |first1=Nathan |title=Forager, Steam's Latest Hit, Is All About The Grind |url=https://kotaku.com/forager-steams-latest-hit-is-all-about-the-grind-1834181112 |website=Kotaku |publisher=Kotaku |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nJeff Ramos on [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] says that the games repetitive and tedious nature serve to \"make the game's bright moments all the brighter\" and says that \"in ''Forager'', grinding is almost all I have to do, and I can hardly pull myself away\" praising the game for its use of grind-heavy mechanics<ref name=\"Polygon-forager\">{{cite web |last1=Ramos |first1=Jeff |title=Forager has some of the best grinding in a video game, and that\u2019s the point - Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/4/26/18516772/forager-game-impressions-pc-linux |website=Polygon |publisher=Polygon |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>.\n\n<br />\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{officialwebsite|https://hopfrogsa.net/forager}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games using procedural generation]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Humble Bundle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Forager\n| image = \n| developer = [[HopFrog]]\n| publisher = [[Humble Bundle]]\n| engine = [[GameMaker Studio]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = {{Collapsible list|title=April 18, 2019|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;background:transparent;text-align:left;\n| '''Microsoft Windows'''|April 18, 2019\n| '''PlayStation 4'''|July 30, 2019\n| '''Nintendo Switch'''|July 30, 2019\n}}\n| genre = [[Open-world]], [[Adventure Game]], [[Survival game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n| director =\n| producer = \n| designer = Mariano Cavallero \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| composer = \n}}\n'''''Forager''''' is an [[open-world]] [[Adventure Game|adventure]] game developed by American studio [[HopFrog]]<ref>https://twitter.com/_hopfrog</ref> and published by [[Humble Bundle]]. The game was officially released for [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[Linux]] in April 2019, later becoming available for [[PlayStation 4]],[[Nintendo Switch]] and [[Xbox One]].\n\nIn ''Forager'', the player progresses by obtaining resources that spawn throughout the world, crafting new buildings, objects, and tools, solving [[Puzzle video game|puzzles]], and collecting money to buy new lands to explore and utilize.\n\n==Gameplay==\nForager combines mechanics commonly seen in [[Incremental_game|idle games]] with those of an adventure or exploration game. <ref name=\"RPS-Forager\">{{cite web |last1=Peel |first1=Jeremy |title=Wot I Think: Forager |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2019/04/26/forager-review/ |website=Rock Paper Shotgun |publisher=Rock Paper Shotgun |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref> With resources that respawn at a very high rate, the player will find themselves able to harvest massive amounts for crafting and leveling, eventually leading to [[Automation|automated]] systems to collect resources and produce other products and goods.\n\nThe leveling system in the game consists of a large grid of unlockable perks, which also may unlock new tools or craftable objects. Everything the player does from harvesting resources, to crafting objects, to killing enemies, has a positive impact on their [[Experience_point|XP]] used to advance levels.\n\nThe player is able to [[Simulation|simulate]] a variety of tasks related to [[cooking]], [[economics]], [[engineering]], [[farming]], [[fishing]], [[hunting]], [[Magic_system|magic]], [[manufacturing]], [[mining]], and more.\n\nBy obtaining money through crafting, skills, looting, and economic tasks, the player is able to purchase more lands to expand their base, explore new areas, and obtain new classes of resources or encounter new enemies and other [[Non-player_character|NPC]].\n\n<br />\n<br />\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| title = \n| state = plain\n| align = right\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = PC:&nbsp;78/100 <ref name=\"Matacritic-Forager\">{{cite web |title=Forager for PC Reviews - Metacritic |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/forager |website=Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref><br />\nNS:&nbsp;75/100<ref name=\"Metacritic-switch\">{{cite web |title=Forager for Switch Reviews - Metacritic |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/forager |website=Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 = [[PCWorld]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"PCWorld-forager\">{{cite web |last1=Dingman |first1=Hayden |title=Forager review: Mindlessly mining the minutes away |url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/3394862/forager-review.html |website=PCWorld |publisher=PCWorld}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Forager'' received \"generally favorable\" reviews, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"Matacritic-Forager\"/> \n\nNathan Grayson wrote a review on [[Kotaku]] calling ''Forager'' an \"extremely well-made\" game and called it \"obviously a labor of love\" while also noting that the game was \"a crafting game stripped down to its very bones\" and stating that players may prefer a game with \"more than pure progression\". <ref name=\"Kotaku-forager-review\">{{cite web |last1=Grayson |first1=Nathan |title=Forager, Steam's Latest Hit, Is All About The Grind |url=https://kotaku.com/forager-steams-latest-hit-is-all-about-the-grind-1834181112 |website=Kotaku |publisher=Kotaku |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nJeff Ramos on [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] says that the games repetitive and tedious nature serve to \"make the game's bright moments all the brighter\" and says that \"in ''Forager'', grinding is almost all I have to do, and I can hardly pull myself away\" praising the game for its use of grind-heavy mechanics<ref name=\"Polygon-forager\">{{cite web |last1=Ramos |first1=Jeff |title=Forager has some of the best grinding in a video game, and that\u2019s the point - Polygon |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/4/26/18516772/forager-game-impressions-pc-linux |website=Polygon |publisher=Polygon |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref>.\n\n<br />\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{officialwebsite|https://hopfrogsa.net/forager}}\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games using procedural generation]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Humble Bundle]]\n", "name_user": "Doctorate821", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added information about the mobile version.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forager_(video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Rape statistics", "text_new": "{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Rape}}\n'''Statistics on rape''' and other [[sexual assault]]s are commonly available in industrialized countries, and are becoming more common throughout the world. Inconsistent [[Rape#Definitions|definitions of rape]], different rates of reporting, recording, prosecution and conviction for [[rape]] create controversial statistical disparities, and lead to accusations that many rape statistics are unreliable or misleading.<ref name=\"Gordon2002\">{{cite book|author=L. P. Gordon|title=Violence Against Women|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rmXf-lSuqcgC|year=2002|publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=978-1-59033-455-3|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=rmXf-lSuqcgC&pg=PA4 4\u20136]}}</ref><ref name=TCJ /> In some jurisdictions, male-female rape is the only form of rape counted in the statistics.<ref name=TCJ>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjonline.com/stories/080804/loc_crimestats.shtml |title=Statistics can be misleading |publisher=CJOnline.com |date=8 August 2004 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> Countries may not define forced sex on a spouse as \"rape\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youthkiawaaz.com/2014/05/forced-intercourse-marriage-rape-says-delhi-court-low-can-stoop/|title=Forced Intercourse In Marriage Not Rape, Says Delhi Court: How Low Can We Stoop? - Youth Ki Awaaz|date=12 May 2014}}</ref> Rape is a severely under-reported crime with surveys showing [[Dark figure of crime|dark figures]] of up to 91.6% of rapes going unreported.<ref>{{cite web|title=ITALIAN NATIONAL STATISTIC INSTITUTE (ISTAT) SURVEY ON VIOLENCE AGAINST WOMEN, 2006 |url=http://sgdatabase.unwomen.org/searchDetail.action?measureId=26309&baseHREF=country&baseHREFId=675 |website=unwomen.org |publisher=UN WOMEN |accessdate=26 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201182537/http://sgdatabase.unwomen.org/searchDetail.action?measureId=26309&baseHREF=country&baseHREFId=675 |archivedate=1 February 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Drug-facilitated, Incapacitated, and Forcible Rape: A National Study|journal=NCJRS|date=February 2007|pages=70|url=https://www.ncjrs.gov/app/publications/abstract.aspx?ID=240972|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> Prevalence of reasons for not reporting rape differ across countries. They may include fear of retaliation, uncertainty about whether a crime was committed or if the offender intended harm, not wanting others to know about the rape, not wanting the offender to get in trouble, fear of prosecution (e.g. due to laws against premarital sex), and doubt in local law enforcement.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Female Victims Of Sexual Violence, 1994-2010|date=7 March 2013|url=http://www.bjs.gov/index.cfm?ty=pbdetail&iid=4594|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Drug-facilitated, Incapacitated, and Forcible Rape: A National Study|journal=Medical University of South Carolina National Crime Victims Research and Treatment CTR|date=February 2007|pages=70}}</ref>\n\nA [[United Nations]] statistical report compiled from government sources showed that more than 250,000 cases of rape or attempted rape were recorded by police annually. The reported data covered 65 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/data-and-analysis/Eighth-United-Nations-Survey-on-Crime-Trends-and-the-Operations-of-Criminal-Justice-Systems.html|title=Eighth United Nations Survey on Crime Trends and the Operations of Criminal Justice Systems |publisher=Unodc.org |date=31 March 2005 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Research==\n[[File:(A) Rape rates per 100000 population 2010-2012, world.jpg|thumb|280px|Reported Rape rates per 100,000 population 2010\u20132012.|alt=]]\n[[File:Listening to girls in Zambia (8220719638).jpg|thumb|In a recent survey of schoolgirls in [[Lusaka]], [[Zambia]], 53% reported that girls in their school have experienced sexual harassment.]]\nMost rape research and reporting to date has been limited to male-female forms of rape. Research on male-male and female-male is beginning to be done. However, almost no research has been done on [[Lesbian rape|female-female rape]], though women can be charged with rape in a few jurisdictions. A few books, such as ''Violent Betrayal: Partner Abuse in Lesbian Relationships'' by Dr. Claire M. Renzetti,<ref>Renzetti, Claire M. ''[https://archive.org/details/violentbetrayalp00renz Violent Betrayal: Partner Abuse in Lesbian Relationships]''. Thousand Oaks, CA: Sage Publications, 1992, {{ISBN|0-8039-3888-8}}.</ref> ''No More Secrets: Violence in Lesbian Relationships'' by Janice Ristock,<ref>Ristock, Janice. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=s00oU23jgPMC&dq=No+More+Secrets:+Violence+in+Lesbian+Relationships&source=bl&ots=UyatauXB9f&sig=b_Vthc4r6fseoM1fM6innbZwhic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=91YZUJ-qIeLW0QWC6oHYDw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA No More Secrets: Violence in Lesbian Relationships]''. New York: Routledge, 2002, {{ISBN|0-415-92946-6}}.</ref> and ''Woman-to-Woman Sexual Violence: Does She Call It Rape?'' by Lori B. Girshick<ref>Girshick, Lori B. ''[https://books.google.com/books/about/Woman_To_Woman_Sexual_Violence.html?id=nHg40DDZWjAC&redir_esc=y Woman-to-Woman Sexual Violence: Does She Call It Rape?] (The Northeastern Series on Gender, Crime, and the Law)''. Boston: Northeastern University Press, 2000, {{ISBN|1-55553-527-5}}.</ref> also cover the topic of rape of women by other women.\n\n==By country==\nThis table indicates the number of, and per capita cases of recorded rape by country. It does not, and of course cannot, include cases of rape which go unreported or unrecorded.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=undata>{{cite web|url=http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/statistics/crime/CTS12_Sexual_violence.xls |title=Statistics : Crime : Sexual Violence (see second tab of spreadsheet) |publisher=Unodc.org |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> It does not specify whether recorded means reported, brought to trial, or convicted. Each entry is based on that country's definition of rape, which varies widely throughout the world. The list does not include the estimated rape statistics of the countries, per year, such as [[South Africa]] having 500,000 rapes per year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report/84909/south-africa-one-in-four-men-rape |title=SOUTH AFRICA: One in four men rape |publisher=Irinnews.org |date=18 June 2009 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> [[China]] having 31,833 rapes a year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uschina.usc.edu/w_usci/showarticle.aspx?articleID=13037&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1 |title=Rape in China, University of Southern California (May 7, 2009) |publisher=Uschina.usc.edu |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> [[Rape in Egypt|Egypt]] having more than 200,000 rapes a year,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapeartistes.com/2012/04/26/how-safe-is-egypt-after-the-revolution/ |title=How Safe is Egypt After the Revolution? Updated 20 June |publisher=Escapeartistes.com |accessdate=2013-12-04|date=26 April 2012 }}</ref> and the United Kingdom at 85,000 rapes a year.<ref name=\"easton1\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"page-break-before:always;\"\n|+ Rape at the national level, number of police-recorded offences<ref name=undata />{{Additional citation needed|date=January 2019|reason=Some of the countries in the table are not in the source}}\n|-\n!\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Total count'''\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Rate per 100,000 population'''\n|-\n! '''Country/territory'''\n! 2003\n! 2004\n! 2005\n! 2006\n! 2007\n! 2008\n! 2009\n! 2010\n! 2003\n! 2004\n! 2005\n! 2006\n! 2007\n! 2008\n! 2009\n! 2010\n\n|-\n| Kenya||||1440||1365||1291||876||735||847||||||4.1||3.8||3.5||2.3||1.9||2.1||\n|-\n| Mauritius||53||40||38||64||77||69||57||51||4.3||3.2||3.0||5.1||6.0||5.4||4.4||3.9\n|-\n| Mozambique||||102||64||46||41||47||44||||||0.5||0.3||0.2||0.2||0.2||0.2||