{"title_page": "Flitwick", "text_new": "{{about|the English town|the Harry Potter character|Filius Flitwick}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.00384|-0.49656|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name= SS Peter and Paul, Flitwick - geograph.org.uk - 345256.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Church of St Peter and St Paul\n| population = 12,700\n| population_ref =<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Office for National Statistics | url = http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=791904&c=Flitwick&d=16&e=15&g=422892&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1202156412656&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779 | title = Neighbourhood Statistics \u2013 Flitwick (CP) Parish | accessdate =4 February 2008 }}</ref><br>  12,998  (2011 Census)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123498&c=Flitwick&d=16&e=62&g=6402568&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1478599731822&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=8 November 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name= Flitwick\n|unitary_england=           [[Central Bedfordshire]]\n|lieutenancy_england =    [[Bedfordshire]]\n|region= East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]]\n|post_town= BEDFORD\n|postcode_district= MK45\n|postcode_area=     MK\n|dial_code= 01525\n|os_grid_reference= TL033350\n}}\n'''Flitwick''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|l|\u026a|t|\u1d7b|k}}), is a small town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in [[Bedfordshire]], England.\nIt is mentioned<ref>See Bedfordshire Virtual Library's [http://www.galaxy.bedfordshire.gov.uk/webingres/bedfordshire/vlib/0.digitised_resources/flitwick_digitisation_timeline.htm Flitwick Timeline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123122625/http://www.galaxy.bedfordshire.gov.uk/webingres/bedfordshire/vlib/0.digitised_resources/flitwick_digitisation_timeline.htm |date=23 November 2008 }}</ref> in the Domesday Book as \"a hamlet on the River Flitt\". The spelling ''Flytwyk'' appears in 1381.<ref>National Archives; Plea Rolls of the Court of Common Pleas; CP 40/483; Year 1381, 4th term; http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT6/R2/CP40no483/483_0207.htm; second entry, home of Richard Hake, the defendant</ref>\n\nThe nearby [[River Flit]] runs through [[Flitwick Moor]], a nature reserve and a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref>Its name is not ancient but a back-formation from Flitton. Ekwall, E. (1940) ''The Concise Dictionary of England Place-names''; 2nd ed. Oxford:Clarendon Press; p. 174.</ref>\n\n==Location==\n\nIt is broadly equidistant between [[Bedford]] {{convert|10|mi|km|abbr=on}} and [[Luton]] {{convert|10|mi|km|abbr=on}}. It shares many services with the neighbouring town of [[Ampthill]], which lies just to the north.  The boundary between the two towns is a watercourse called the Running Waters, which is now the route of the A507.\n\n==Nearby settlements==\n\n[[Ampthill]], [[Maulden]], [[Clophill]], [[Flitton]], [[Greenfield, Bedfordshire|Greenfield]], [[Steppingley]], [[Pulloxhill]], [[Westoning]], [[Harlington, Bedfordshire|Harlington]], [[Barton le Clay]], [[Tingrith]], [[Eversholt]], [[Millbrook, Bedfordshire|Millbrook]]\n\n==Shopping==\n\nFlitwick has seen a large expansion in its population in recent years, but its retail facilities have not kept up with this growth. The local council has drawn up plans to redevelop the town centre to improve its retail offering [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-12535915]. At present, it has a [[Tesco]], a [[Barclays]] bank, a [[The Co-operative Group|Co-op]], which provides a secondary food source to the community and many smaller shops and estate agents, many in close proximity to the railway station. There is an open-air market every Friday selling local produce, which is set up on the car park of the village hall. The open-air market has a variety of stalls such as fishmongers, baker, haberdashery, and fruit and vegetables.\n\n==Leisure==\nThere is a sports centre with a 25-metre swimming pool with kids pool attached. The leisure centre also has a gym, squash courts with leagues and gymnasium. A new leisure centre was built for opening in early March 2015. The existing leisure site is earmarked by Central Beds Council for downsizing and over 55 assisted living accommodation.\n\nFlitwick Town Council own and operate from The Rufus Centre on the outskirts of the town on Steppingley Road. The Centre is also a busy conference and special event venue with office space to lease.\n\nFlitwick has four pubs; the Crown, the Swan, the Bumble Bee and the Blackbirds. The Blackbirds is a 17th-century building with a large beer garden and children's play area.  The pub formerly known as the Wheatsheaf re-opened as an Indian restaurant called the Indian Lodge. A membership-operated social club, The Flitwick Club, is situated on The High Street, opposite the Drivestyle yard.\n\n[[Center Parcs Woburn Forest]] opened in July 2014 on the outskirts of Flitwick at Warren Wood.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\nFlitwick is {{convert|5|mi|km|abbr=on}} from junction 12 of the [[M1 motorway]].\n\n===Bus===\n\nThe main bus services are as follows:\n\n42 (Grant Palmer) provides an hourly daytime service Mondays to Saturdays providing a connection to: Westoning, Harlington, Toddington, Ampthill, Houghton Conquest, and Bedford.  Mondays to Saturdays \u2013 no Sunday service.\n\n42 (Stagecoach) provides an hourly daytime service Mondays to Saturdays to Ampthill,   Kempston and Bedford.  Mondays to Saturdays \u2013 no Sunday service.\n\n44 (Grant Palmer) Bedford via A6 to Bedford, Wilstead, Flitwick, Silsoe (Monday - Friday Only)\n\n200 (Grant Palmer) provides a two hourly service to Ampthill, Shefford, Clifton and Biggleswade.  Mondays to Fridays only.\n\n34 (Grant Palmer) Milton Keynes\n\n===Rail===\n\nFlitwick has a [[Flitwick railway station|station]] on the Thameslink line (First Capital Connect took over the franchise on 1 April 2006, taken over again on 14 September 2014 by Govia Thameslink Railway). Trains go north to Bedford and south to Luton, St Albans, London, Gatwick Airport, Three Bridges, East Grinstead and Brighton making it a popular place to live for commuters.\n\n==Schools==\n\nFlitwick has three lower schools (Kingsmoor, Templefield and Flitwick Lower School), a middle school (Woodland School). The old Flitwick School has been refurbished from its earlier state of neglect, and now serves as a further community centre, youth club and toddler group. Redborne Upper School is approximately {{convert|1|mi|km}} away from Flitwick Railway Station, just on the Ampthill side of the Running Waters.<ref>http://www.ampthill.info/page12.htm</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n{{See also|Sport in Bedfordshire}}\nIt has four football teams: Flitwick Town, who play in the Bedfordshire County League Premier Division, Flitwick Ladies, who play in the Bedfordshire & Hertfordshire Women's First Division, Flitwick Eagles, and Dinamo Flitwick.\nIt is also home to Flitwick Cricket Club (The Otters) which has over 50 adult playing members and 160 Colts.\n\n==Landmarks==\nFlitwick is famous for its [[Flitwick Manor]] House, currently used as a hotel and restaurant.\n\nThere is also physical evidence of a Norman fortification, [[Flitwick Castle]], locally known as \"The Mount\".\n\nThe medieval [[Church of St Peter & St Paul, Flitwick|Church of St Peter & St Paul]] is the parish church, located in the town.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Brian Stein]], former [[Luton Town]] professional footballer, lives in Flitwick.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n*[[Adam Croft]], an international best-selling writer of [[crime fiction]].\n*[[Michael Crowther]], prominent American wildlife conservationist and founder of the Indianapolis Prize, grew up in Flitwick, living there from age 4 until age 17. He attended Flitwick Primary School and Bedford Modern School.\n*Jesse Billington, zoologist and travel writer. Billington grew up in Flitwick and attended [[Bedford School]] from the ages of 6-18 before going to the [[University of Reading]] to read zoology. Since then he has gone on to become a published travel writer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Englishman-Abroad-Ecuador-Gal%C3%A1pagos-Islands/dp/1080540288/ref=sr_1_7?keywords=englishman+abroad&qid=1574291323&sr=8-7|title=Amazon.com: An Englishman Abroad; Ecuador and the Galapagos Islands.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and a food journalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foodtribe.com/u/EpiDOlC_QPO5ZucgLWUCkg|title=Jesse Billington's Profile|website=FoodTribe|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.flitwick.gov.uk Flitwick Town Council]\n\n{{Bedfordshire}}\n{{Places in Bedfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Flitwick|*]]\n[[Category:Central Bedfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the English town|the Harry Potter character|Filius Flitwick}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.00384|-0.49656|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name= SS Peter and Paul, Flitwick - geograph.org.uk - 345256.jpg\n|static_image_caption= Church of St Peter and St Paul\n| population = 12,700\n| population_ref =<ref>{{cite web | publisher = Office for National Statistics | url = http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=3&b=791904&c=Flitwick&d=16&e=15&g=422892&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1202156412656&enc=1&dsFamilyId=779 | title = Neighbourhood Statistics \u2013 Flitwick (CP) Parish | accessdate =4 February 2008 }}</ref><br>  12,998  (2011 Census)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123498&c=Flitwick&d=16&e=62&g=6402568&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1478599731822&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=8 November 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n|official_name= Flitwick\n|unitary_england=           [[Central Bedfordshire]]\n|lieutenancy_england =    [[Bedfordshire]]\n|region= East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Mid Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Bedfordshire]]\n|post_town= BEDFORD\n|postcode_district= MK45\n|postcode_area=     MK\n|dial_code= 01525\n|os_grid_reference= TL033350\n}}\n'''Flitwick''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|l|\u026a|t|\u1d7b|k}}), is a small town and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in [[Bedfordshire]], England.\nIt is mentioned<ref>See Bedfordshire Virtual Library's [http://www.galaxy.bedfordshire.gov.uk/webingres/bedfordshire/vlib/0.digitised_resources/flitwick_digitisation_timeline.htm Flitwick Timeline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123122625/http://www.galaxy.bedfordshire.gov.uk/webingres/bedfordshire/vlib/0.digitised_resources/flitwick_digitisation_timeline.htm |date=23 November 2008 }}</ref> in the Domesday Book as \"a hamlet on the River Flitt\". The spelling ''Flytwyk'' appears in 1381.<ref>National Archives; Plea Rolls of the Court of Common Pleas; CP 40/483; Year 1381, 4th term; http://aalt.law.uh.edu/AALT6/R2/CP40no483/483_0207.htm; second entry, home of Richard Hake, the defendant</ref>\n\nThe nearby [[River Flit]] runs through [[Flitwick Moor]], a nature reserve and a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].<ref>Its name is not ancient but a back-formation from Flitton. Ekwall, E. (1940) ''The Concise Dictionary of England Place-names''; 2nd ed. Oxford:Clarendon Press; p. 174.</ref>\n\n==Location==\n\nIt is broadly equidistant between [[Bedford]] {{convert|10|mi|km|abbr=on}} and [[Luton]] {{convert|10|mi|km|abbr=on}}. It shares many services with the neighbouring town of [[Ampthill]], which lies just to the north.  The boundary between the two towns is a watercourse called the Running Waters, which is now the route of the A507.\n\n==Nearby settlements==\n\n[[Ampthill]], [[Maulden]], [[Clophill]], [[Flitton]], [[Greenfield, Bedfordshire|Greenfield]], [[Steppingley]], [[Pulloxhill]], [[Westoning]], [[Harlington, Bedfordshire|Harlington]], [[Barton le Clay]], [[Tingrith]], [[Eversholt]], [[Millbrook, Bedfordshire|Millbrook]]\n\n==Shopping==\n\nFlitwick has seen a large expansion in its population in recent years, but its retail facilities have not kept up with this growth. The local council has drawn up plans to redevelop the town centre to improve its retail offering [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-12535915]. At present, it has a [[Tesco]], a [[Barclays]] bank, a [[The Co-operative Group|Co-op]], which provides a secondary food source to the community and many smaller shops and estate agents, many in close proximity to the railway station. There is an open-air market every Friday selling local produce, which is set up on the car park of the village hall. The open-air market has a variety of stalls such as fishmongers, baker, haberdashery, and fruit and vegetables.\n\n==Leisure==\nThere is a sports centre with a 25-metre swimming pool with kids pool attached. The leisure centre also has a gym, squash courts with leagues and gymnasium. A new leisure centre was built for opening in early March 2015. The existing leisure site is earmarked by Central Beds Council for downsizing and over 55 assisted living accommodation.\n\nFlitwick Town Council own and operate from The Rufus Centre on the outskirts of the town on Steppingley Road. The Centre is also a busy conference and special event venue with office space to lease.\n\nFlitwick has four pubs; the Crown, the Swan, the Bumble Bee and the Blackbirds. The Blackbirds is a 17th-century building with a large beer garden and children's play area.  The pub formerly known as the Wheatsheaf re-opened as an Indian restaurant called the Indian Lodge. A membership-operated social club, The Flitwick Club, is situated on The High Street, opposite the Drivestyle yard.\n\n[[Center Parcs Woburn Forest]] opened in July 2014 on the outskirts of Flitwick at Warren Wood.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\nFlitwick is {{convert|5|mi|km|abbr=on}} from junction 12 of the [[M1 motorway]].\n\n===Bus===\n\nThe main bus services are as follows:\n\n42 (Grant Palmer) provides an hourly daytime service Mondays to Saturdays providing a connection to: Westoning, Harlington, Toddington, Ampthill, Houghton Conquest, and Bedford.  Mondays to Saturdays \u2013 no Sunday service.\n\n42 (Stagecoach) provides an hourly daytime service Mondays to Saturdays to Ampthill,   Kempston and Bedford.  Mondays to Saturdays \u2013 no Sunday service.\n\n44 (Grant Palmer) Bedford via A6 to Bedford, Wilstead, Flitwick, Silsoe (Monday - Friday Only)\n\n200 (Grant Palmer) provides a two hourly service to Ampthill, Shefford, Clifton and Biggleswade.  Mondays to Fridays only.\n\n34 (Grant Palmer) Milton Keynes\n\n===Rail===\n\nFlitwick has a [[Flitwick railway station|station]] on the Thameslink line (First Capital Connect took over the franchise on 1 April 2006, taken over again on 14 September 2014 by Govia Thameslink Railway). Trains go north to Bedford and south to Luton, St Albans, London, Gatwick Airport, Three Bridges, East Grinstead and Brighton making it a popular place to live for commuters.\n\n==Schools==\n\nFlitwick has three lower schools (Kingsmoor, Templefield and Flitwick Lower School), a middle school (Woodland School). The old Flitwick School has been refurbished from its earlier state of neglect, and now serves as a further community centre, youth club and toddler group. It is also in close proximity to Redborne Upper School (approx 2 miles away).\n\n==Sport==\n{{See also|Sport in Bedfordshire}}\nIt has four football teams: Flitwick Town, who play in the Bedfordshire County League Premier Division, Flitwick Ladies, who play in the Bedfordshire & Hertfordshire Women's First Division, Flitwick Eagles, and Dinamo Flitwick.\nIt is also home to Flitwick Cricket Club (The Otters) which has over 50 adult playing members and 160 Colts.\n\n==Landmarks==\nFlitwick is famous for its [[Flitwick Manor]] House, currently used as a hotel and restaurant.\n\nThere is also physical evidence of a Norman fortification, [[Flitwick Castle]], locally known as \"The Mount\".\n\nThe medieval [[Church of St Peter & St Paul, Flitwick|Church of St Peter & St Paul]] is the parish church, located in the town.\n\n== Notable people ==\n* [[Brian Stein]], former [[Luton Town]] professional footballer, lives in Flitwick.{{citation needed|date=October 2018}}\n*[[Adam Croft]], an international best-selling writer of [[crime fiction]].\n*[[Michael Crowther]], prominent American wildlife conservationist and founder of the Indianapolis Prize, grew up in Flitwick, living there from age 4 until age 17. He attended Flitwick Primary School and Bedford Modern School.\n*Jesse Billington, zoologist and travel writer. Billington grew up in Flitwick and attended [[Bedford School]] from the ages of 6-18 before going to the [[University of Reading]] to read zoology. Since then he has gone on to become a published travel writer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Englishman-Abroad-Ecuador-Gal%C3%A1pagos-Islands/dp/1080540288/ref=sr_1_7?keywords=englishman+abroad&qid=1574291323&sr=8-7|title=Amazon.com: An Englishman Abroad; Ecuador and the Galapagos Islands.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and a food journalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foodtribe.com/u/EpiDOlC_QPO5ZucgLWUCkg|title=Jesse Billington's Profile|website=FoodTribe|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.flitwick.gov.uk Flitwick Town Council]\n\n{{Bedfordshire}}\n{{Places in Bedfordshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Flitwick|*]]\n[[Category:Central Bedfordshire District]]\n", "name_user": "Mjb1981", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSchools:rephrased Redborne, made distance more specific.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flitwick"}
{"title_page": "Breast imaging", "text_new": "{{for|non-medical images of breasts|Depictions of nudity}}\n[[File:Breast imaging using pet (1).jpg|thumb|[[Positron emission mammography]] is one of several methods of breast imaging.]]\n\nIn medicine, '''breast imaging''' is the representation or reproduction of a breast's form. There are various methods of breast imaging.\n\n==X-ray==\n\n===Mammography===\n{{main|Mammography}}\n\n[[File:Diagnosis - Mammography.jpg|thumb|The best mammographic images are produced when the breast is compressed.]]\n\nMammography is the process of using low-energy [[X-ray]]s (usually around 30 [[Peak kilovoltage|kVp]]) to examine the human [[breast]], which is used as a diagnostic and screening tool. The goal of mammography is the early detection of [[breast cancer]], typically through detection of characteristic masses and/or [[microcalcification]]s. \n\nFor the average woman, the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force|U.S. Preventive Services Task Force]] recommended (2009) mammography every two years in women between the ages of 50 and 74.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Topic/recommendation-summary/breast-cancer-screening |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |accessdate=}}</ref> The American College of Radiology and American Cancer Society recommend yearly screening mammography starting at age 40.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breast Cancer Early Detection|url=http://www.cancer.org/cancer/breastcancer/moreinformation/breastcancerearlydetection/breast-cancer-early-detection-acs-recs|website=cancer.org|accessdate=29 July 2014|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> The Canadian Task Force on Preventive Health Care (2012) and the European Cancer Observatory (2011) recommends mammography every 2\u20133 years between 50 and 69.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/183/17/1991.full |title=Recommendations on screening for breast cancer in average-risk women aged 40\u201374 years |accessdate=2013-02-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html,en |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211011840/http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html%2Cen |archivedate=2012-02-11 }}</ref> While the ACR notes that more infrequent screening would miss about a third of cancers and result in up to 10,000 cancer deaths<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Henrick|first=R. Edward|date=Feb 2011|title=United States Preventative Task Force Screening Mammography: Science Ignored|url=https://www.ajronline.org/doi/full/10.2214/AJR.10.5609?hits=10&author1=hendrick&sortspec=relevance&searchid=1&maxtoshow=&FIRSTINDEX=0&resourcetype=HWCIT&RESULTFORMAT=|journal=American Journal of Roentgenology|volume=196|pages=|via=}}</ref>, the task forces aforementioned also note that more frequent mammogram include a small but significant increase in breast cancer induced by radiation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastCancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616040709/http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastcancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |archivedate=2013-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"Friedenson00\">{{cite journal | author = Friedenson B | title = Is mammography indicated for women with defective BRCA genes? Implications of recent scientific advances for the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of hereditary breast cancer | journal = MedGenMed | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = E9 |date= March 2000 | pmid = 11104455 | doi =  | url = http://www.medscape.com/Medscape/GeneralMedicine/journal/2000/v02.n02/mgm0309.frie/mgm0309.frie-01.html }}</ref> It should also be noted that mammography overall has a false-negative (missed cancer) rate of between 7 and 12 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww5.komen.org/BreastCancer/AccuracyofMammograms.html|title=Mammogram Accuracy - Accuracy of Mammograms|website=ww5.komen.org|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> This is partly due to [[optical density|dense]] tissues obscuring the cancer and the fact that the appearance of cancer on mammograms has a large overlap with the appearance of normal tissues. Additionally, mammogram should not be done with any increased frequency in people undergoing breast surgery, including breast enlargement, mastopexy, and breast reducation.<ref>{{Citation|author1=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |author1-link=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |date=24 April 2014 |title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |accessdate=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719103909/http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |archivedate=19 July 2014 }}</ref> \n\nIn a study later done by the [[Cochrane Collaboration]] (2013), it concluded that the trials with adequate randomisation did not find an effect of mammography screening on total cancer mortality, including breast cancer, after 10 years. The authors of systematic review write: \"If we assume that screening reduces breast cancer mortality by 15% and that overdiagnosis and overtreatment is at 30%, it means that for every 2000 women invited for screening throughout 10 years, one will avoid dying of breast cancer and 10 healthy women, who would not have been diagnosed if there had not been screening, will be treated unnecessarily. Furthermore, more than 200 women will experience important psychological distress including anxiety and uncertainty for years because of false positive findings.\"  The authors go on to conclude that the time has come to re-assess whether universal mammography screening should be recommended for any age group.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=G\u00f8tzsche PC, J\u00f8rgensen KJ | title = Screening for breast cancer with mammography | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume =  6| issue = 6 | pages = CD001877 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23737396 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001877.pub5 | pmc=6464778}}</ref> Presently, Cochrane Collaboration recommends that women should at least be informed of the benefits and harms of mammography screening and have written an evidence-based leaflet in several languages that can be found on www.cochrane.dk.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn addition to diagnostic purposes, mammography has utility in stereotactic biopsies to precisely locate and find the area of concern and guide the biopsy needle to this precise location. This ensures that the area biopsies correlates to the abnormality seen on mammogram. It\u2019s called stereotactic since it utilizes images taken from two different angles of the same location. A biopsy is indicated when small accumulations of calcium are seen on mammogram, but can\u2019t be felt on physical exam and don\u2019t appear on ultrasound.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthline.com/health/breast-biopsy-stereotactic|title=Stereotactic Breast Biopsy: Purpose, Procedure & Risks|website=Healthline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Digital Breast Tomosynthesis (DBT) ====\nDigital breast [[tomosynthesis]] (DBT) can provide a higher diagnostic accuracy compared to conventional mammography. The key to understanding DBT is analogous to understanding the difference between an x-ray and CT.  Specifically, one is three dimensional whereas the other is flat. A mammogram usually takes two x-rays of each breast from different angles whereas digital tomosynthesis creates a 3-dimensional picture of the breast using x-rays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breastcancer.org/symptoms/testing/types/dig_tomosynth|title=Digital Tomosynthesis|date=2016-06-23|website=Breastcancer.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn DBT, like conventional mammography, compression is used to improve image quality and decreases radiation dose.  The laminographic imaging technique dates back to the 1930s and belongs to the category of geometric or linear tomography.<ref>Dedicated Computed Tomography of the Breast: Image Processing and Its Impact on Breast Mass Detectability. Qing Xia. 2007. {{ISBN|0549663193}} pp.4</ref> Because the data acquired are very high resolution (85 \u2013 160 micron typical ), much higher than CT, DBT is unable to offer the  narrow slice widths that CT offers (typically 1-1.5&nbsp;mm). However, the higher resolution detectors permit very high in-plane resolution, even if the Z-axis resolution is less. The primary interest in DBT is in breast imaging, as an extension to [[mammography]], where it offers better detection rates .<ref>Smith AP, Niklason L, Ren B, Wu T, Ruth C, Jing Z. Lesion Visibility in Low Dose Tomosynthesis. In: Digital mammography : 8th international workshop, IWDM 2006, Manchester, UK, June 18\u201321, 2006 : proceedings. Astley, S, Brady, M, Rose, C, Zwiggelaar, R (Eds.) (Springer, New York, 2006) pp.160.</ref><ref name=\"L\u00e5ngAndersson2014\">{{cite journal |last1=L\u00e5ng| first1=K |last2=Andersson |first2=I |last3=Zackrisson |first3=S |title=Breast cancer detection in digital breast tomosynthesis and digital mammography\u2014a side-by-side review of discrepant cases |journal=The British Journal of Radiology |volume=87 |issue=1040 |year=2014 |pages=20140080 |issn=0007-1285 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20140080 |pmid=24896197 |pmc=4112403}}</ref>\n\nA recent study also looked at the radiation dose delivered by conventional mammography compared to DBT. While this study found that while there was a modest decrease in radiation dose delivery by digital mammography, the study concluded that the small dose increase should not prevent providers from using tomosynthesis given the evidence for potential clinical benefit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gennaro|first=Gisella|last2=Bernardi|first2=D.|last3=Houssami|first3=N.|date=February 2018|title=Radiation dose with digital breast tomosynthesis compared to digital mammography: per-view analysis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28819862|journal=European Radiology|volume=28|issue=2|pages=573\u2013581|doi=10.1007/s00330-017-5024-4|issn=1432-1084|pmid=28819862}}</ref>\n\nTomosynthesis is also now [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved for use in [[breast cancer screening]].<ref>\"[https://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/ProductsandMedicalProcedures/DeviceApprovalsandClearances/Recently-ApprovedDevices/ucm246400.htm Selenia Dimensions 3D System \u2013 P080003], US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), February 11, 2011</ref> Digital breast tomosynthesis is associated with a higher detection of poor prognosis cancers compared to digital mammography.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Conant|first=Emily F.|last2=Zuckerman|first2=Samantha P.|last3=McDonald|first3=Elizabeth S.|last4=Weinstein|first4=Susan P.|last5=Korhonen|first5=Katrina E.|last6=Birnbaum|first6=Julia A.|last7=Tobey|first7=Jennifer D.|last8=Schnall|first8=Mitchell D.|last9=Hubbard|first9=Rebecca A.|date=2020-03-10|title=Five Consecutive Years of Screening with Digital Breast Tomosynthesis: Outcomes by Screening Year and Round|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32154771|journal=Radiology|pages=191751|doi=10.1148/radiol.2020191751|issn=1527-1315|pmid=32154771}}</ref> since it is able to overcome the primary limitation of standard 2D mammography which had a masking effect due to the overlapping fibroglandular tissue, whereas DBT is able to distinguish between benign and malignant features, particularly in dense breasts.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gilbert|first=Fiona J.|title=Diagnosis and Staging of Breast Cancer: When and How to Use Mammography, Tomosynthesis, Ultrasound, Contrast-Enhanced Mammography, and Magnetic Resonance Imaging|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553859/|work=Diseases of the Chest, Breast, Heart and Vessels 2019-2022: Diagnostic and Interventional Imaging|editor-last=Hodler|editor-first=Juerg|series=IDKD Springer Series|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-030-11148-9|pmid=32096932|access-date=2020-04-11|last2=Pinker-Domenig|first2=Katja|editor2-last=Kubik-Huch|editor2-first=Rahel A.|editor3-last=von Schulthess|editor3-first=Gustav K.}}</ref> DBT has also been found to be a reliable tool for intraoperative surgical margin assessment in non-palpable lesions thus reducing the volume of breast excision without increasing the risk of cancer recurrence.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lehman|first=Constance D.|last2=Lee|first2=Amie Y.|last3=Lee|first3=Christoph I.|date=November 2014|title=Imaging management of palpable breast abnormalities|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25341156|journal=AJR. American journal of roentgenology|volume=203|issue=5|pages=1142\u20131153|doi=10.2214/AJR.14.12725|issn=1546-3141|pmid=25341156}}</ref>\n\n==== Xeromammography ====\n{{main|Xeromammography}}\nXeromammography is a [[photoelectric]] method of recording an [[x-ray]] image on a coated metal plate, using low-energy [[photon]] beams, long exposure time, and dry chemical developers. It is a form of [[xeroradiography]].<ref>{{MeshName|Xeromammography}}</ref>\n\nRadiation exposure is an important factor in risk assessment since it makes up 98% of the effective dose. Currently, the mean value of the absorbed dose in the glandular tissue is used as a description of radiation risk since the glandular tissue is the most vulnerable part of the breast.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00e4bel|first=M.|last2=Aichinger|first2=U.|last3=Schulz-Wendtland|first3=R.|date=February 2001|title=[Radiation exposure in x-ray mammography]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11253092|journal=RoFo: Fortschritte Auf Dem Gebiete Der Rontgenstrahlen Und Der Nuklearmedizin|volume=173|issue=2|pages=79\u201391|doi=10.1055/s-2001-10888|issn=1438-9029|pmid=11253092}}</ref>\n\n===Galactography===\n{{main|Galactography}}\nGalactography is a medical diagnostic procedure for viewing the [[milk ducts]]. It is considered a useful procedure in the early diagnosis of patients with pathologic nipple discharge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bern\u00e1-Serna|first=Juan D.|last2=Torres-Ales|first2=Carolina|last3=Bern\u00e1-Mestre|first3=Juan D.|last4=Polo|first4=Luis|date=May 2013|title=Role of galactography in the early diagnosis of breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24419050|journal=Breast Care (Basel, Switzerland)|volume=8|issue=2|pages=122\u2013126|doi=10.1159/000350779|issn=1661-3791|pmc=3683945|pmid=24419050}}</ref> The standard treatment of galactographically suspicious breast lesions is to perform a surgical intervention on the concerned duct or ducts: if the discharge clearly stems from a single duct, then the excision of the duct ([[microdochectomy]]) is indicated;<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\">{{cite book|author1=Nigel Rawlinson|author2=Derek Alderson|title=Surgery: Diagnosis and Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxbDsuew0IkC&pg=PA219|date=29 September 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9122-0|pages=219}}</ref> if the discharge comes from several ducts or if no specific duct could be determined, then a subareolar resection of the ducts ([[Hadfield's procedure]]) is performed instead.<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\"/> To avoid infection, galactography should not be performed when the nipple discharge contains [[pus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-ductography-1|title=Breast ductography|publisher=radiopaedia.org|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere is also some utility for tomosynthesis to be used with galactography. In a study publicshed by Schulz-Wendtland R et al., investgators made more mistakes when using only ductal sonography compared to when they used contrast-enhanced galactography with tomosyntheiss which allowed for generated synthetic digital 2D full-field mammograms to diagnose suspicious lesions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chand|first=Jithin T.|last2=Sharma|first2=Mala M.|last3=Dharmarajan|first3=Janaki P.|last4=Nambiar|first4=Ajit|date=December 2019|title=Digital Breast Tomosynthesis as a Tool in Confirming Negative Surgical Margins in Non-palpable Breast Lesions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31857754|journal=Indian Journal of Surgical Oncology|volume=10|issue=4|pages=624\u2013628|doi=10.1007/s13193-019-00956-z|issn=0975-7651|pmc=6895353|pmid=31857754}}</ref>\n\n==MRI==\n{{main|Breast MRI}}\n\n[[File:Mri of breast.jpg|thumb|A color-enhanced MRI of a breast]]\n\nBreast MRI, an alternative to mammography, has shown substantial progress in the detection of breast cancer. The available literature suggests that the [[Sensitivity and specificity|sensitivity]] of contrast-enhanced breast MRI in detection of cancer is considerably higher than that of either radiographic mammography or [[ultrasound]] and is generally reported to be in excess of 94%.<ref name=Goscin2001>[http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/409021_9 Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the Breast]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Sensitivity and specificity|specificity]]'' (the confidence that a lesion is cancerous and not a [[false positive]]) is only fair ('modest'),<ref name=\"pmid18342764\">{{cite journal |vauthors=DeMartini W, Lehman C, Partridge S |title=Breast MRI for cancer detection and characterization: a review of evidence-based clinical applications |journal=Acad Radiol |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=408\u201316 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18342764 |doi=10.1016/j.acra.2007.11.006 }}</ref> (or 37%-97%<ref name=Goscin2001/>) thus a ''positive'' finding by MRI should not be interpreted as a definitive diagnosis.\n\nThe reports of 4,271 breast MRIs from eight large scale clinical trials were reviewed in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Lehman CD | title=Role of MRI in screening women at high risk for breast cancer | journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance Imaging | volume=24 | issue=5 | year=2006  | pages=964\u201370 | pmid=17036340 | doi=10.1002/jmri.20752}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, American and European guidelines both recommend MRI screening as the optimum imaging modality but differences exist in regards to screening for certain patient subgroups. Specifically, the advantage of MRI screening is increased detection of small cancers which have less associated lymph node involvement and consequently decreased frequency of interval cancers which affect survival and mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roca|first=S. Alonso|date=31 March 2020|title=Screening in Patients with Increased Risk of Breast Cancer. Pros and Cons of MRI Screening.|url=https://www.elsevier.es/es-revista-radiologia-119-avance-resumen-cribado-pacientes-con-riesgo-incrementado-S0033833820300308#tbl0020|journal=Radiologia|volume=62|pages=237\u2013249|via=Elsevier}}</ref>  MRI has also shown specific utility in women with extremely dense breast tissue. By using supplemental MRI in these women who had otherwise normal mammography results, there was a diagnosis of significantly fewer interval cancers than when using mammography alone during a two year period.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bakker|first=Marije F.|date=November 2019|title=Supplemental MRI Screening for Women with Extremely Dense Breast Tissue|url=|journal=NEJM|volume=381|pages=2091-2102|via=}}</ref> Additionally, MRI Is also shown to be more accurate than mammography, ultrasound, or clinical exam in evaluating treatment response to neo-adjuvant therapy<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reig|first=Beatriu|last2=Heacock|first2=Laura|last3=Lewin|first3=Alana|last4=Cho|first4=Nariya|last5=Moy|first5=Linda|date=2020-03-29|title=Role of MRI to Assess Response to Neoadjuvant Therapy for Breast Cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32227407|journal=Journal of magnetic resonance imaging: JMRI|doi=10.1002/jmri.27145|issn=1522-2586|pmid=32227407}}</ref>\n\n==Ultrasound==\n{{main|Breast ultrasound}}\n\n[[File:Ultrasound Scan ND 115254 1159140 cr.png|thumb|Breast ultrasounds may be used with or without a mammogram.]]\n\nBreast ultrasound is the use of [[medical ultrasonography]] to perform imaging of the [[breast]]. It can be considered either a [[diagnostic procedure|diagnostic]] or a [[screening (medicine)|screening]] procedure.<ref name=\"StavrosRapp2004\">{{cite book|author1=A. Thomas Stavros|author2=Cynthia L. Rapp|author3=Steve H. Parker|title=Breast ultrasound|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UkGtw5VI15sC|accessdate=22 August 2010|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-0-397-51624-7}}</ref> It may be used either with or without a mammogram.<ref name=\"urlBreast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003379.htm|title=Breast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|website=|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\nDiagnostic anatomic ultrasound looks at the anatomy whereas diagnostic functional ultrasound records information such as blood flow or tissue characteristics. A specific functional form of ultrasound is elastography which measures and displays the relative elasticity of tissues, which can be used to differentiate tumors from healthy tissue.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nibib.nih.gov/science-education/science-topics/magnetic-resonance-imaging-mri|title=Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)|website=www.nibib.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Recent studies have shown that shear wave elastography in primary invasive breast carcinoma could be useful for indicating axillary lymphadenopathy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wen|first=Xin|last2=Yu|first2=Xiwen|last3=Tian|first3=Yuhang|last4=Liu|first4=Zhao|last5=Cheng|first5=Wen|last6=Li|first6=Hairu|last7=Kang|first7=Jia|last8=Wei|first8=Tianci|last9=Yuan|first9=Shasha|last10=Tian|first10=Jiawei|date=March 2020|title=Quantitative shear wave elastography in primary invasive breast cancers, based on collagen-S100A4 pathology, indicates axillary lymph node metastasis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32269923|journal=Quantitative Imaging in Medicine and Surgery|volume=10|issue=3|pages=624\u2013633|doi=10.21037/qims.2020.02.18|issn=2223-4292|pmc=7136724|pmid=32269923|via=}}</ref>\n\nUltrasound also has operative utility. Specifically, an ultrasound-guided needle biopsy allows providers to see the needle so it can be directed toward the target (ex: a breast tumor) while avoiding other critical structures (ex: vasculature).<ref name=\":0\" /> Through this use of ultrasound, it has also shown to decrease re-excision and mastectomy rates in breast cancer.  A recent study found 100% ultrasound localization with negative margins obtained in both non-palpable and palpable lesions at initial procedure. In line with this, intraoperative ultrasound guided breast conserving surgery is being increasingly used by breast surgeons worldwide<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karadeniz Cakmak|first=Guldeniz|last2=Emre|first2=Ali U.|last3=Tascilar|first3=Oge|last4=Bahadir|first4=Burak|last5=Ozkan|first5=Selcuk|date=June 2017|title=Surgeon performed continuous intraoperative ultrasound guidance decreases re-excisions and mastectomy rates in breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28273552|journal=Breast (Edinburgh, Scotland)|volume=33|pages=23\u201328|doi=10.1016/j.breast.2017.02.014|issn=1532-3080|pmid=28273552|via=}}</ref>\n\nContrast-enhanced Ultrasound (CEUS) Imaging has also been researched and shows similar sensitivity to MRI in detecting breast cancer across lesions of similar size. Additionally, the combined use of MRI and CEUS in lesions > 20 mm has been shown to optimize the diagnostic specificity and accuracy in breast cancer prediction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Chunxiao|last2=Yao|first2=Minghua|last3=Shao|first3=Sihui|last4=Li|first4=Xin|last5=Li|first5=Gang|last6=Wu|first6=Rong|date=2020-04-07|title=Diagnostic efficacy of contrast-enhanced ultrasound for breast lesions of different sizes: a comparative study with magnetic resonance imaging|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32216631|journal=The British Journal of Radiology|pages=20190932|doi=10.1259/bjr.20190932|issn=1748-880X|pmid=32216631}}</ref> \n\n==Scintimammography==\n{{main|Scintimammography}}\nScintimammography is a type of [[breast]] imaging test that is used to detect [[cancer cells]] in the breasts of some women who have had abnormal [[mammogram]]s, or for those who have dense [[breast tissue]], [[breast surgery|post-operative]] scar tissue or [[breast implant]]s, but is not used for [[Breast cancer screening|screening]] or in place of a mammogram. Rather, it is used when the detection of breast abnormalities is not possible or not reliable on the basis of mammography and [[breast ultrasound|ultrasound]]. In the scintimammography procedure, a [[woman]] receives an [[Injection (medicine)|injection]] of a small amount of a [[radioactive]] substance called [[technetium]] 99 [[sestamibi]]. This substance is preferably taken up by cancerous tissues, making them show brightly on the images.<ref name=\"NassHenderson2001\">{{cite book|last1=Nass|first1=Sharyl J.|last2=Henderson|first2=I. Craig|last3=Cancer|first3=Institute of Medicine (U.S.). Committee on Technologies for the Early Detection of Breast|title=Mammography and beyond: developing technologies for the early detection of breast cancer|url=https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2011|year=2001|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-07283-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0/page/n131 106]\u2013}}</ref> Research has also shown that Tc-99 Sestamibi wash out rate is a reliable test for predicting tumor response to neoadjuvant chemotherapy in locally advanced breast cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Trehan|first=Romeeta|last2=Seam|first2=Rajeev K.|last3=Gupta|first3=Manoj K.|last4=Sood|first4=Ashwani|last5=Dimri|first5=Kislay|last6=Mahajan|first6=Rohit|date=September 2014|title=Role of scintimammography in assessing the response of neoadjuvant chemotherapy in locally advanced breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25538487|journal=World Journal of Nuclear Medicine|volume=13|issue=3|pages=163\u2013169|doi=10.4103/1450-1147.144816|issn=1450-1147|pmc=4262874|pmid=25538487|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Breast procedures}}\n\n[[Category:Breast imaging|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|non-medical images of breasts|Depictions of nudity}}\n[[File:Breast imaging using pet (1).jpg|thumb|[[Positron emission mammography]] is one of several methods of breast imaging.]]\n\nIn medicine, '''breast imaging''' is the representation or reproduction of a breast's form. There are various methods of breast imaging.\n\n==X-ray==\n\n===Mammography===\n{{main|Mammography}}\n\n[[File:Diagnosis - Mammography.jpg|thumb|The best mammographic images are produced when the breast is compressed.]]\n\nMammography is the process of using low-energy [[X-ray]]s (usually around 30 [[Peak kilovoltage|kVp]]) to examine the human [[breast]], which is used as a diagnostic and screening tool. The goal of mammography is the early detection of [[breast cancer]], typically through detection of characteristic masses and/or [[microcalcification]]s. For the average woman, the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force|U.S. Preventive Services Task Force]] recommended (2009) mammography every two years in women between the ages of 50 and 74.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Topic/recommendation-summary/breast-cancer-screening |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |accessdate=}}</ref> The American College of Radiology and American Cancer Society recommend yearly screening mammography starting at age 40.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breast Cancer Early Detection|url=http://www.cancer.org/cancer/breastcancer/moreinformation/breastcancerearlydetection/breast-cancer-early-detection-acs-recs|website=cancer.org|accessdate=29 July 2014|date=2013-09-17}}</ref> The Canadian Task Force on Preventive Health Care (2012) and the European Cancer Observatory (2011) recommends mammography every 2\u20133 years between 50 and 69.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmaj.ca/content/183/17/1991.full |title=Recommendations on screening for breast cancer in average-risk women aged 40\u201374 years |accessdate=2013-02-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html,en |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211011840/http://eu-cancer.iarc.fr/cancer-13-breast-screening.html%2Cen |archivedate=2012-02-11 }}</ref> While the ACR notes that more infrequent screening would miss about a third of cancers and result in up to 10,000 cancer deaths<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Henrick|first=R. Edward|date=Feb 2011|title=United States Preventative Task Force Screening Mammography: Science Ignored|url=https://www.ajronline.org/doi/full/10.2214/AJR.10.5609?hits=10&author1=hendrick&sortspec=relevance&searchid=1&maxtoshow=&FIRSTINDEX=0&resourcetype=HWCIT&RESULTFORMAT=|journal=American Journal of Roentgenology|volume=196|pages=|via=}}</ref>, the task forces aforementioned also note that more frequent mammogram include a small but significant increase in breast cancer induced by radiation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastCancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |title=Breast Cancer: Screening |work=United States Preventive Services Task Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616040709/http://www.ahrq.gov/clinic/3rduspstf/breastcancer/brcanrr.htm#ref31 |archivedate=2013-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=Friedenson00>{{cite journal | author = Friedenson B | title = Is mammography indicated for women with defective BRCA genes? Implications of recent scientific advances for the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of hereditary breast cancer | journal = MedGenMed | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = E9 |date= March 2000 | pmid = 11104455 | doi =  | url = http://www.medscape.com/Medscape/GeneralMedicine/journal/2000/v02.n02/mgm0309.frie/mgm0309.frie-01.html }}</ref> It should also be noted that mammography overall has a false-negative (missed cancer) rate of between 7 and 12 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww5.komen.org/BreastCancer/AccuracyofMammograms.html|title=Mammogram Accuracy - Accuracy of Mammograms|website=ww5.komen.org|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref> This is partly due to [[optical density|dense]] tissues obscuring the cancer and the fact that the appearance of cancer on mammograms has a large overlap with the appearance of normal tissues. Additionally, mammogram should not be done with any increased frequency in people undergoing breast surgery, including breast enlargement, mastopexy, and breast reducation.<ref>{{Citation|author1=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |author1-link=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |date=24 April 2014 |title=Five Things Physicians and Patients Should Question |publisher=American Society of Plastic Surgeons |work=[[Choosing Wisely]]: an initiative of the [[ABIM Foundation]] |url=http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |accessdate=25 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719103909/http://www.choosingwisely.org/doctor-patient-lists/american-society-of-plastic-surgeons/ |archivedate=19 July 2014 }}</ref> \n\nIn a study later done by the [[Cochrane Collaboration]] (2013), it concluded that the trials with adequate randomisation did not find an effect of mammography screening on total cancer mortality, including breast cancer, after 10 years. The authors of systematic review write: \"If we assume that screening reduces breast cancer mortality by 15% and that overdiagnosis and overtreatment is at 30%, it means that for every 2000 women invited for screening throughout 10 years, one will avoid dying of breast cancer and 10 healthy women, who would not have been diagnosed if there had not been screening, will be treated unnecessarily. Furthermore, more than 200 women will experience important psychological distress including anxiety and uncertainty for years because of false positive findings.\"  The authors go on to conclude that the time has come to re-assess whether universal mammography screening should be recommended for any age group.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |vauthors=G\u00f8tzsche PC, J\u00f8rgensen KJ | title = Screening for breast cancer with mammography | journal = Cochrane Database Syst Rev | volume =  6| issue = 6 | pages = CD001877 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23737396 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD001877.pub5 | pmc=6464778}}</ref> Presently, Cochrane Collaboration recommends that women should at least be informed of the benefits and harms of mammography screening and have written an evidence-based leaflet in several languages that can be found on www.cochrane.dk.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn addition to diagnostic purposes, mammography has utility in stereotactic biopsies to precisely locate and find the area of concern and guide the biopsy needle to this precise location. This ensures that the area biopsies correlates to the abnormality seen on mammogram. It\u2019s called stereotactic since it utilizes images taken from two different angles of the same location. A biopsy is indicated when small accumulations of calcium are seen on mammogram, but can\u2019t be felt on physical exam and don\u2019t appear on ultrasound.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healthline.com/health/breast-biopsy-stereotactic|title=Stereotactic Breast Biopsy: Purpose, Procedure & Risks|website=Healthline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Digital Breast Tomosynthesis (DBT) ====\nDigital breast [[tomosynthesis]] (DBT) can provide a higher diagnostic accuracy compared to conventional mammography. The key to understanding DBT is analogous to understanding the difference between an x-ray and CT.  Specifically, one is three dimensional whereas the other is flat. A mammogram usually takes two x-rays of each breast from different angles whereas digital tomosynthesis creates a 3-dimensional picture of the breast using x-rays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breastcancer.org/symptoms/testing/types/dig_tomosynth|title=Digital Tomosynthesis|date=2016-06-23|website=Breastcancer.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn DBT, like conventional mammography, compression is used to improve image quality and decreases radiation dose.  The laminographic imaging technique dates back to the 1930s and belongs to the category of geometric or linear tomography.<ref>Dedicated Computed Tomography of the Breast: Image Processing and Its Impact on Breast Mass Detectability. Qing Xia. 2007. {{ISBN|0549663193}} pp.4</ref> Because the data acquired are very high resolution (85 \u2013 160 micron typical ), much higher than CT, DBT is unable to offer the  narrow slice widths that CT offers (typically 1-1.5&nbsp;mm). However, the higher resolution detectors permit very high in-plane resolution, even if the Z-axis resolution is less. The primary interest in DBT is in breast imaging, as an extension to [[mammography]], where it offers better detection rates .<ref>Smith AP, Niklason L, Ren B, Wu T, Ruth C, Jing Z. Lesion Visibility in Low Dose Tomosynthesis. In: Digital mammography : 8th international workshop, IWDM 2006, Manchester, UK, June 18\u201321, 2006 : proceedings. Astley, S, Brady, M, Rose, C, Zwiggelaar, R (Eds.) (Springer, New York, 2006) pp.160.</ref><ref name=\"L\u00e5ngAndersson2014\">{{cite journal |last1=L\u00e5ng| first1=K |last2=Andersson |first2=I |last3=Zackrisson |first3=S |title=Breast cancer detection in digital breast tomosynthesis and digital mammography\u2014a side-by-side review of discrepant cases |journal=The British Journal of Radiology |volume=87 |issue=1040 |year=2014 |pages=20140080 |issn=0007-1285 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20140080 |pmid=24896197 |pmc=4112403}}</ref>\n\nA recent study also looked at the radiation dose delivered by conventional mammography compared to DBT. While this study found that while there was a modest decrease in radiation dose delivery by digital mammography, the study concluded that the small dose increase should not prevent providers from using tomosynthesis given the evidence for potential clinical benefit.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gennaro|first=Gisella|last2=Bernardi|first2=D.|last3=Houssami|first3=N.|date=February 2018|title=Radiation dose with digital breast tomosynthesis compared to digital mammography: per-view analysis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28819862|journal=European Radiology|volume=28|issue=2|pages=573\u2013581|doi=10.1007/s00330-017-5024-4|issn=1432-1084|pmid=28819862}}</ref>\n\nTomosynthesis is also now [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) approved for use in [[breast cancer screening]].<ref>\"[https://www.fda.gov/MedicalDevices/ProductsandMedicalProcedures/DeviceApprovalsandClearances/Recently-ApprovedDevices/ucm246400.htm Selenia Dimensions 3D System \u2013 P080003], US Food and Drug Administration (FDA), February 11, 2011</ref> Digital breast tomosynthesis is associated with a higher detection of poor prognosis cancers compared to digital mammography.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Conant|first=Emily F.|last2=Zuckerman|first2=Samantha P.|last3=McDonald|first3=Elizabeth S.|last4=Weinstein|first4=Susan P.|last5=Korhonen|first5=Katrina E.|last6=Birnbaum|first6=Julia A.|last7=Tobey|first7=Jennifer D.|last8=Schnall|first8=Mitchell D.|last9=Hubbard|first9=Rebecca A.|date=2020-03-10|title=Five Consecutive Years of Screening with Digital Breast Tomosynthesis: Outcomes by Screening Year and Round|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32154771|journal=Radiology|pages=191751|doi=10.1148/radiol.2020191751|issn=1527-1315|pmid=32154771}}</ref> since it is able to overcome the primary limitation of standard 2D mammography which had a masking effect due to the overlapping fibroglandular tissue, whereas DBT is able to distinguish between benign and malignant features, particularly in dense breasts.<ref>{{Citation|last=Gilbert|first=Fiona J.|title=Diagnosis and Staging of Breast Cancer: When and How to Use Mammography, Tomosynthesis, Ultrasound, Contrast-Enhanced Mammography, and Magnetic Resonance Imaging|date=2019|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553859/|work=Diseases of the Chest, Breast, Heart and Vessels 2019-2022: Diagnostic and Interventional Imaging|editor-last=Hodler|editor-first=Juerg|series=IDKD Springer Series|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-030-11148-9|pmid=32096932|access-date=2020-04-11|last2=Pinker-Domenig|first2=Katja|editor2-last=Kubik-Huch|editor2-first=Rahel A.|editor3-last=von Schulthess|editor3-first=Gustav K.}}</ref> DBT has also been found to be a reliable tool for intraoperative surgical margin assessment in non-palpable lesions thus reducing the volume of breast excision without increasing the risk of cancer recurrence.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lehman|first=Constance D.|last2=Lee|first2=Amie Y.|last3=Lee|first3=Christoph I.|date=November 2014|title=Imaging management of palpable breast abnormalities|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25341156|journal=AJR. American journal of roentgenology|volume=203|issue=5|pages=1142\u20131153|doi=10.2214/AJR.14.12725|issn=1546-3141|pmid=25341156}}</ref>\n\n==== Xeromammography ====\n{{main|Xeromammography}}\nXeromammography is a [[photoelectric]] method of recording an [[x-ray]] image on a coated metal plate, using low-energy [[photon]] beams, long exposure time, and dry chemical developers. It is a form of [[xeroradiography]].<ref>{{MeshName|Xeromammography}}</ref>\n\nRadiation exposure is an important factor in risk assessment since it makes up 98% of the effective dose. Currently, the mean value of the absorbed dose in the glandular tissue is used as a description of radiation risk since the glandular tissue is the most vulnerable part of the breast.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=S\u00e4bel|first=M.|last2=Aichinger|first2=U.|last3=Schulz-Wendtland|first3=R.|date=February 2001|title=[Radiation exposure in x-ray mammography]|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11253092|journal=RoFo: Fortschritte Auf Dem Gebiete Der Rontgenstrahlen Und Der Nuklearmedizin|volume=173|issue=2|pages=79\u201391|doi=10.1055/s-2001-10888|issn=1438-9029|pmid=11253092}}</ref>\n\n===Galactography===\n{{main|Galactography}}\nGalactography is a medical diagnostic procedure for viewing the [[milk ducts]]. It is considered a useful procedure in the early diagnosis of patients with pathologic nipple discharge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bern\u00e1-Serna|first=Juan D.|last2=Torres-Ales|first2=Carolina|last3=Bern\u00e1-Mestre|first3=Juan D.|last4=Polo|first4=Luis|date=May 2013|title=Role of galactography in the early diagnosis of breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24419050|journal=Breast Care (Basel, Switzerland)|volume=8|issue=2|pages=122\u2013126|doi=10.1159/000350779|issn=1661-3791|pmc=3683945|pmid=24419050}}</ref> The standard treatment of galactographically suspicious breast lesions is to perform a surgical intervention on the concerned duct or ducts: if the discharge clearly stems from a single duct, then the excision of the duct ([[microdochectomy]]) is indicated;<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\">{{cite book|author1=Nigel Rawlinson|author2=Derek Alderson|title=Surgery: Diagnosis and Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fxbDsuew0IkC&pg=PA219|date=29 September 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9122-0|pages=219}}</ref> if the discharge comes from several ducts or if no specific duct could be determined, then a subareolar resection of the ducts ([[Hadfield's procedure]]) is performed instead.<ref name=\"RawlinsonAlderson2010-p219\"/> To avoid infection, galactography should not be performed when the nipple discharge contains [[pus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiopaedia.org/articles/breast-ductography-1|title=Breast ductography|publisher=radiopaedia.org|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere is also some utility for tomosynthesis to be used with galactography. In a study publicshed by Schulz-Wendtland R et al., investgators made more mistakes when using only ductal sonography compared to when they used contrast-enhanced galactography with tomosyntheiss which allowed for generated synthetic digital 2D full-field mammograms to diagnose suspicious lesions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chand|first=Jithin T.|last2=Sharma|first2=Mala M.|last3=Dharmarajan|first3=Janaki P.|last4=Nambiar|first4=Ajit|date=December 2019|title=Digital Breast Tomosynthesis as a Tool in Confirming Negative Surgical Margins in Non-palpable Breast Lesions|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31857754|journal=Indian Journal of Surgical Oncology|volume=10|issue=4|pages=624\u2013628|doi=10.1007/s13193-019-00956-z|issn=0975-7651|pmc=6895353|pmid=31857754}}</ref>\n\n==MRI==\n{{main|Breast MRI}}\n\n[[File:Mri of breast.jpg|thumb|A color-enhanced MRI of a breast]]\n\nBreast MRI, an alternative to mammography, has shown substantial progress in the detection of breast cancer. The available literature suggests that the [[Sensitivity and specificity|sensitivity]] of contrast-enhanced breast MRI in detection of cancer is considerably higher than that of either radiographic mammography or [[ultrasound]] and is generally reported to be in excess of 94%.<ref name=Goscin2001>[http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/409021_9 Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the Breast]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Sensitivity and specificity|specificity]]'' (the confidence that a lesion is cancerous and not a [[false positive]]) is only fair ('modest'),<ref name=\"pmid18342764\">{{cite journal |vauthors=DeMartini W, Lehman C, Partridge S |title=Breast MRI for cancer detection and characterization: a review of evidence-based clinical applications |journal=Acad Radiol |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=408\u201316 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18342764 |doi=10.1016/j.acra.2007.11.006 }}</ref> (or 37%-97%<ref name=Goscin2001/>) thus a ''positive'' finding by MRI should not be interpreted as a definitive diagnosis.\n\nThe reports of 4,271 breast MRIs from eight large scale clinical trials were reviewed in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Lehman CD | title=Role of MRI in screening women at high risk for breast cancer | journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance Imaging | volume=24 | issue=5 | year=2006  | pages=964\u201370 | pmid=17036340 | doi=10.1002/jmri.20752}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, American and European guidelines both recommend MRI screening as the optimum imaging modality but differences exist in regards to screening for certain patient subgroups. Specifically, the advantage of MRI screening is increased detection of small cancers which have less associated lymph node involvement and consequently decreased frequency of interval cancers which affect survival and mortality.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roca|first=S. Alonso|date=31 March 2020|title=Screening in Patients with Increased Risk of Breast Cancer. Pros and Cons of MRI Screening.|url=https://www.elsevier.es/es-revista-radiologia-119-avance-resumen-cribado-pacientes-con-riesgo-incrementado-S0033833820300308#tbl0020|journal=Radiologia|volume=62|pages=237\u2013249|via=Elsevier}}</ref>  MRI has also shown specific utility in women with extremely dense breast tissue. By using supplemental MRI in these women who had otherwise normal mammography results, there was a diagnosis of significantly fewer interval cancers than when using mammography alone during a two year period.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bakker|first=Marije F.|date=November 2019|title=Supplemental MRI Screening for Women with Extremely Dense Breast Tissue|url=|journal=NEJM|volume=381|pages=2091-2102|via=}}</ref> Additionally, MRI Is also shown to be more accurate than mammography, ultrasound, or clinical exam in evaluating treatment response to neo-adjuvant therapy<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reig|first=Beatriu|last2=Heacock|first2=Laura|last3=Lewin|first3=Alana|last4=Cho|first4=Nariya|last5=Moy|first5=Linda|date=2020-03-29|title=Role of MRI to Assess Response to Neoadjuvant Therapy for Breast Cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32227407|journal=Journal of magnetic resonance imaging: JMRI|doi=10.1002/jmri.27145|issn=1522-2586|pmid=32227407}}</ref>\n\n==Ultrasound==\n{{main|Breast ultrasound}}\n\n[[File:Ultrasound Scan ND 115254 1159140 cr.png|thumb|Breast ultrasounds may be used with or without a mammogram.]]\n\nBreast ultrasound is the use of [[medical ultrasonography]] to perform imaging of the [[breast]]. It can be considered either a [[diagnostic procedure|diagnostic]] or a [[screening (medicine)|screening]] procedure.<ref name=\"StavrosRapp2004\">{{cite book|author1=A. Thomas Stavros|author2=Cynthia L. Rapp|author3=Steve H. Parker|title=Breast ultrasound|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UkGtw5VI15sC|accessdate=22 August 2010|date=1 January 2004|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-0-397-51624-7}}</ref> It may be used either with or without a mammogram.<ref name=\"urlBreast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003379.htm|title=Breast ultrasound: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|website=|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\nDiagnostic anatomic ultrasound looks at the anatomy whereas diagnostic functional ultrasound records information such as blood flow or tissue characteristics. A specific functional form of ultrasound is elastography which measures and displays the relative elasticity of tissues, which can be used to differentiate tumors from healthy tissue.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nibib.nih.gov/science-education/science-topics/magnetic-resonance-imaging-mri|title=Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI)|website=www.nibib.nih.gov|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Recent studies have shown that shear wave elastography in primary invasive breast carcinoma could be useful for indicating axillary lymphadenopathy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wen|first=Xin|last2=Yu|first2=Xiwen|last3=Tian|first3=Yuhang|last4=Liu|first4=Zhao|last5=Cheng|first5=Wen|last6=Li|first6=Hairu|last7=Kang|first7=Jia|last8=Wei|first8=Tianci|last9=Yuan|first9=Shasha|last10=Tian|first10=Jiawei|date=March 2020|title=Quantitative shear wave elastography in primary invasive breast cancers, based on collagen-S100A4 pathology, indicates axillary lymph node metastasis|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32269923|journal=Quantitative Imaging in Medicine and Surgery|volume=10|issue=3|pages=624\u2013633|doi=10.21037/qims.2020.02.18|issn=2223-4292|pmc=7136724|pmid=32269923|via=}}</ref>\n\nUltrasound also has operative utility. Specifically, an ultrasound-guided needle biopsy allows providers to see the needle so it can be directed toward the target (ex: a breast tumor) while avoiding other critical structures (ex: vasculature).<ref name=\":0\" /> Through this use of ultrasound, it has also shown to decrease re-excision and mastectomy rates in breast cancer.  A recent study found 100% ultrasound localization with negative margins obtained in both non-palpable and palpable lesions at initial procedure. In line with this, intraoperative ultrasound guided breast conserving surgery is being increasingly used by breast surgeons worldwide<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karadeniz Cakmak|first=Guldeniz|last2=Emre|first2=Ali U.|last3=Tascilar|first3=Oge|last4=Bahadir|first4=Burak|last5=Ozkan|first5=Selcuk|date=June 2017|title=Surgeon performed continuous intraoperative ultrasound guidance decreases re-excisions and mastectomy rates in breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28273552|journal=Breast (Edinburgh, Scotland)|volume=33|pages=23\u201328|doi=10.1016/j.breast.2017.02.014|issn=1532-3080|pmid=28273552|via=}}</ref>\n\nContrast-enhanced Ultrasound (CEUS) Imaging has also been researched and shows similar sensitivity to MRI in detecting breast cancer across lesions of similar size. Additionally, the combined use of MRI and CEUS in lesions > 20 mm has been shown to optimize the diagnostic specificity and accuracy in breast cancer prediction.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=Chunxiao|last2=Yao|first2=Minghua|last3=Shao|first3=Sihui|last4=Li|first4=Xin|last5=Li|first5=Gang|last6=Wu|first6=Rong|date=2020-04-07|title=Diagnostic efficacy of contrast-enhanced ultrasound for breast lesions of different sizes: a comparative study with magnetic resonance imaging|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32216631|journal=The British Journal of Radiology|pages=20190932|doi=10.1259/bjr.20190932|issn=1748-880X|pmid=32216631}}</ref> \n\n==Scintimammography==\n{{main|Scintimammography}}\nScintimammography is a type of [[breast]] imaging test that is used to detect [[cancer cells]] in the breasts of some women who have had abnormal [[mammogram]]s, or for those who have dense [[breast tissue]], [[breast surgery|post-operative]] scar tissue or [[breast implant]]s, but is not used for [[Breast cancer screening|screening]] or in place of a mammogram. Rather, it is used when the detection of breast abnormalities is not possible or not reliable on the basis of mammography and [[breast ultrasound|ultrasound]]. In the scintimammography procedure, a [[woman]] receives an [[Injection (medicine)|injection]] of a small amount of a [[radioactive]] substance called [[technetium]] 99 [[sestamibi]]. This substance is preferably taken up by cancerous tissues, making them show brightly on the images.<ref name=\"NassHenderson2001\">{{cite book|last1=Nass|first1=Sharyl J.|last2=Henderson|first2=I. Craig|last3=Cancer|first3=Institute of Medicine (U.S.). Committee on Technologies for the Early Detection of Breast|title=Mammography and beyond: developing technologies for the early detection of breast cancer|url=https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0|url-access=registration|accessdate=17 July 2011|year=2001|publisher=National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-07283-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mammographybeyon00comm_0/page/n131 106]\u2013}}</ref> Research has also shown that Tc-99 Sestamibi wash out rate is a reliable test for predicting tumor response to neoadjuvant chemotherapy in locally advanced breast cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Trehan|first=Romeeta|last2=Seam|first2=Rajeev K.|last3=Gupta|first3=Manoj K.|last4=Sood|first4=Ashwani|last5=Dimri|first5=Kislay|last6=Mahajan|first6=Rohit|date=September 2014|title=Role of scintimammography in assessing the response of neoadjuvant chemotherapy in locally advanced breast cancer|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25538487|journal=World Journal of Nuclear Medicine|volume=13|issue=3|pages=163\u2013169|doi=10.4103/1450-1147.144816|issn=1450-1147|pmc=4262874|pmid=25538487|via=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Breast procedures}}\n\n[[Category:Breast imaging|*]]\n", "name_user": "Amircha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMammography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breast_imaging"}
{"title_page": "Legoland Discovery Centre", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name          = LEGOLAND Discovery Centre\n| logo          = Legoland Discovery Centre logo.svg\n| image         = Legoland Discovery Centre Manchester.JPG\n| image_caption = Legoland Discovery Centre at [[Trafford Centre]]\n| locations     = 28 (by 2023)\n| owner         = [[Merlin Entertainments]]<br />[[Lego Group]]\n| homepage      = {{URL|legolanddiscoverycenter.com}}\n}}\n'''Legoland Discovery Centre''' is an indoor [[family entertainment center|family attraction]] chain operated by British leisure group [[Merlin Entertainments]]. Featuring models and attractions inspired by the [[Lego]] building toys, the Discovery Centres are smaller versions of the [[Legoland]] [[theme park]]s located around the world.\n\n==Attractions==\nA typical Legoland Discovery Centre occupies approximately {{convert|30000|-|35000|sqft|m2|-1}} of floor area.<ref name=\"AJC1023\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ajc.com/business/legoland-scouting-atlanta-sites-171227.html?cxntlid=thbz_hm\n|title=Legoland scouting Atlanta sites. Is a wax museum next?\n|author=Rachel Tobin Ramos\n|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution\n|date=2009-10-23\n|accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\"SunTimes\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.suntimes.com/lifestyles/travel/extras/1006187,TRA-News-legoside15.article\n |title       = A little local Legoland headed our way\n |author      = Andrew Herrmann\n |work        = Chicago Sun-Times\n |date        = 2008-06-15\n |accessdate  = 2009-10-24\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100303120149/http://www.suntimes.com/lifestyles/travel/extras/1006187,TRA-News-legoside15.article\n |archivedate = 2010-03-03\n}}</ref>\n\nDiscovery Centres include models of local landmarks rendered in LEGO\u00ae bricks. Visitors can also learn how the LEGO\u00ae bricks are manufactured or partake in building classes taught by a Master Model Builder. Certain locations may also include [[4-D film|4-D movie theatres]] offering multiple showings throughout the day. \n\nA number of children's attractions, such as small rides and play fortresses, are also available. The centres can host birthday parties as well as scholastic and group functions and also include restaurants and gift shops selling Lego merchandise.\n\n==Reception==\nThe target audience for the Legoland Discovery Centre is families with young children, normally ages 3 through 12;<ref name=\"ManEN\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1123912_legoland_to_open_at_trafford_centre\n|title=Legoland to open at Trafford Centre\n|author=Paul R. Taylor\n|work=Manchester Evening News\n|date=2009-07-01\n|accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref> though a typical location's average guest is about seven years of age.<ref name=\"AJC1023\"/> Discovery Centres are located near other family-friendly attractions and dining establishments.<ref name=\"AJC1023\"/> In a given year, a single facility can host approximately 400,000 to 600,000 visitors.<ref name=\"AJC1023\"/>\n\n==Locations==\n\n{{multiple image\n | align             = right\n | direction         = vertical\n | header            = <center>Legoland Discovery Centres</center>\n | header_align      = center\n | header_background = \n | footer            = \n | footer_align      = left\n | footer_background = \n | width             = \n | image1            = Entrance to Legoland Discovery Centre Berlin.jpg\n | width1            = 179\n | alt1              = \n | caption1          = <center>Legoland Discovery Centre Berlin</center>\n | image2            = ExtraSchicht 2011-07 \u2013 Duisburg, Innenhafen \u2013 CN-08.JPG\n | width2            = 185\n | alt2              = \n | caption2          = <center>Legoland Discovery Centre Duisburg</center>\n | image3            = LegolandDiscoveryCentreToronto.JPG\n | width3            = 185\n | alt3              = \n | caption3          = <center>Legoland Discovery Centre Toronto</center>\n}}\n\n{{As of|September 2018}}, Legoland Discovery Centres are operating in 22 different locations:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legolanddiscoverycenter.com/|title=Jump inside the world's biggest box of LEGO\u00ae bricks at a LEGOLAND\u00ae Discovery Center|website=Jump inside the world's biggest box of LEGO\u00ae bricks at a LEGOLAND\u00ae Discovery Center|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n'''United States'''\n* Arizona&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Phoenix at [[Arizona Mills]] in [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]]\n* Atlanta&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Atlanta at [[Phipps Plaza]] in Buckhead in [[Atlanta]]\n* Boston&nbsp;\u2013 [[Legoland Discovery Center Boston]] at Assembly Row in [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]]\n* Chicago&nbsp;\u2013 [[Legoland Discovery Center Chicago]] at [[The Streets of Woodfield]] in [[Schaumburg, Illinois|Schaumburg]]\n* Columbus \u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Columbus at [[Easton Town Center]] in [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]]\n* Dallas/Fort Worth&nbsp;\u2013 [[Legoland Discovery Center Dallas Fort Worth]] at [[Grapevine Mills]] in [[Grapevine, Texas|Grapevine]]\n* Kansas City&nbsp;\u2013 [[Legoland Discovery Center Kansas City]] at [[Crown Center]] in [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]\n* Michigan&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Michigan at [[Great Lakes Crossing Outlets]] in [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]]\n* Philadelphia&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Philadelphia at [[Plymouth Meeting Mall]] in [[Plymouth Meeting, Pennsylvania|Plymouth Meeting]]\n* Westchester&nbsp;\u2013 [[Legoland Discovery Center Westchester]] at [[Westchester's Ridge Hill]] in [[Yonkers]]\n* San Antonio \u2013 Legoland Discovery Center San Antonio at [[Shops at Rivercenter]] in [[San Antonio]]\n\n'''Canada'''\n* Toronto&nbsp;\u2013 [[LEGOLAND Discovery Centre Toronto|Legoland Discovery Centre Toronto]] at [[Vaughan Mills]] in [[Vaughan]]\n'''Europe'''\n* Birmingham \u2013 Legoland Discovery Centre Birmingham at [[Arena Birmingham]] in [[Birmingham]], United Kingdom\n* Berlin \u2013 Legoland Discovery Centre Berlin at the [[Sony Center]] in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]\n* Istanbul&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Istanbul in [[Bayrampa\u015fa|Bayrampasa]], [[Istanbul]]\n* Manchester&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Centre Manchester at [[Trafford Centre]], [[Greater Manchester]], United Kingdom<ref name=\"ManEN\" />\n* Oberhausen&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Oberhausen in [[Oberhausen]], [[Germany]]\n'''Asia'''\n* Osaka&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Osaka at [[Tempozan Market Place]] in [[Osaka]], [[Japan]]\n* Shanghai&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Shanghai at [[Joy City Changfeng]] in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]\n* Tokyo&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Center Tokyo at Decks Mall in [[Odaiba]], [[Tokyo]], Japan\n'''Australia'''\n* Melbourne&nbsp;\u2013 Legoland Discovery Centre Melbourne at [[Chadstone Shopping Centre]] in [[Melbourne, Australia]]\n* Mt Hotham - Legoland Discovery Centre Hotham - at the [[Merlin Entertainments]] owned [[Hotham Alpine Resort]]. Operated July to October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.snowsbest.com/legoland-comes-to-hotham-for-school-holidays/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-12-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216163651/https://www.snowsbest.com/legoland-comes-to-hotham-for-school-holidays/ |archive-date=2018-12-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''China'''\n\n* Shenyang- Legoland Discovery Center at K11 Center in Shenyang, China<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legolanddiscoverycenter.cn/shenyang-en/|title=Legoland Discovery Center k11 Center|last=|first=|date=|website=LEGOLAND Discovery Center.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.legolanddiscoverycenter.cn/shenyang-en/|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==Future locations==\n{{update section|date=June 2019}}\n* A Legoland Discovery Center was scheduled to open in mid 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2017/02/scheveningen-to-get-legoland-discovery-centre/|title=Scheveningen to get Legoland Discovery Centre|date=3 February 2017|website=DutchNews.nl|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref> in The Hague, Netherlands but is now scheduled for 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bollenstreek.nl/dagje-uit/pretpark/legoland-nederland-discovery-center-opent-in-2019-in-scheveningen/|title=EGOLAND\u00ae Nederland Discovery Center opens in 2020 in Scheveningen|website=bollenstreek.nl|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n* In January 2017, Merlin Entertainments Indian subsidiary stated that it was in discussion with real estate firms to open Legoland Discovery Centres in multiple cities in India.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/ZV9MSwuGNtC6o1FqBqDcWP/After-Madame-Tussauds-Merlin-set-to-bring-Legoland-Sea-Lif.html|title=After Madame Tussauds, Merlin set to bring Legoland, Sea Life to India|last=Agarwal|first=Sapna|date=2017-01-17|website=Livemint.com|access-date=2018-10-14}}</ref>\n* A Legoland Discovery Center is scheduled to open in Spring 2020 at [[American Dream Meadowlands]], [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nj.com/bergen/2019/08/these-2-american-dream-amusements-wont-open-until-2020.html|title=These 2 American Dream amusements won\u2019t open until 2020|last=NJ.com|first=Allison Pries {{!}} NJ Advance Media for|date=2019-08-05|website=nj|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n*A Legoland Discovery Center is scheduled to open in 2023 at [[American Dream Miami]], [[Miami]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article211285629.html|title=Five things to watch for as Miami-Dade prepares for American Dream mega-mall vote|website=Miamiherald.com|access-date=2018-10-14|language=en}}</ref>\n*A Legoland Discovery Center is scheduled to open in 2020 at [[Great Mall of the Bay Area]], [[Milpitas, California|Milpitas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanjose.legolanddiscoverycenter.com/|title=LEGOLAND Discovery Center San Jose {{!}} The Ultimate Indoor LEGO Playground|website=San Jose|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref>\n*A Legoland Discovery Center is scheduled to open in early 2021 in [[Pittsburgh]] at [[The Mall at Robinson]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.legolanddiscoverycenter.com/|title=LEGOLAND Discovery Center Pittsburgh {{!}} The Ultimate Indoor LEGO Playground|website=Pittsburgh|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Legoland Discovery Centre}}\n* [http://www.legolanddiscoverycenter.com Official home page]\n\n{{Legoland}}\n{{lego}}\n{{Merlin Entertainments}}\n\n[[Category:Legoland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name          = LEGOLAND Discovery Centre\n| logo          = Legoland Discovery Centre logo.svg\n| image         = Legoland Discovery Centre Manchester.JPG\n| image_caption = Legoland Discovery Centre at [[Trafford Centre]]\n| locations     = 28 (by 2023)\n| owner         = [[Merlin Entertainments]]<br />[[Lego Group]]\n| homepage      = {{URL|legolanddiscoverycenter.com}}\n}}\n'''Legoland Discovery Centre''' is an indoor [[family entertainment center|family attraction]] chain operated by British leisure group [[Merlin Entertainments]]. Featuring models and attractions inspired by the [[Lego]] building toys, the Discovery Centres are smaller versions of the [[Legoland]] [[theme park]]s located around the world.\n\n==Attractions==\nA typical Legoland Discovery Centre occupies approximately {{convert|30000|-|35000|sqft|m2|-1}} of floor area.<ref name=\"AJC1023\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.ajc.com/business/legoland-scouting-atlanta-sites-171227.html?cxntlid=thbz_hm\n|title=Legoland scouting Atlanta sites. Is a wax museum next?\n|author=Rachel Tobin Ramos\n|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution\n|date=2009-10-23\n|accessdate=2009-10-24}}</ref><ref name=\"SunTimes\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.suntimes.com/lifestyle